---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import { amortizationSchedule } from "../../lib/calc/loan";

const title = "If I Pay $300 Extra on My Mortgage (what changes?)";
const description =
  "Paying $300 extra toward principal can shorten payoff time and reduce interest. Learn what changes, what to confirm with your lender, and model scenarios.";

const examplePrincipal = 300000;
const exampleApr = 6.5;
const exampleTermMonths = 360;
const exampleExtraMonthly = 300;
const base = amortizationSchedule({ principal: examplePrincipal, aprPercent: exampleApr, termMonths: exampleTermMonths });
const withExtra = amortizationSchedule({
  principal: examplePrincipal,
  aprPercent: exampleApr,
  termMonths: exampleTermMonths,
  extraMonthly: exampleExtraMonthly
});
const money0 = new Intl.NumberFormat("en-US", { style: "currency", currency: "USD", minimumFractionDigits: 0, maximumFractionDigits: 0 });
const pct2 = new Intl.NumberFormat("en-US", { minimumFractionDigits: 2, maximumFractionDigits: 2 });
---
<BaseLayout title={title} description={description} canonicalPath="/guides/pay-300-extra-on-mortgage" robots="noindex, follow">
  <section class="card hero">
    <span class="pill">Guide</span>
    <nav class="breadcrumbs" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
      <a href="/">Home</a>
      <span aria-hidden="true">/</span>
      <a href="/guides">Guides</a>
      <span aria-hidden="true">/</span>
      <span aria-current="page">Pay $300 extra</span>
    </nav>
    <h1>If I pay $300 extra on my mortgage, what happens?</h1>
    <p>
      If the extra amount is applied as principal-only, you reduce the loan balance sooner. That usually reduces total interest and can
      shorten your payoff timeline. This guide explains the mechanics and what to check so the payment is applied the way you expect.
    </p>
    <div class="btn-row">
      <a class="btn" href="/topics/mortgage-payoff">Mortgage payoff topic hub</a>
      <a class="btn btn-primary" href="/calculators/extra-payment-calculator">Extra payment mortgage calculator</a>
      <a class="btn" href="/guides/principal-only-extra-payments">Principal-only checklist</a>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="card section prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">What changes (and what usually doesn't)</h2>
    <ul class="muted" style="margin:10px 0 0; padding-left:18px">
      <li><strong>Usually changes:</strong> payoff date (earlier), total interest (lower), and the amortization schedule.</li>
      <li><strong>Usually doesn't change:</strong> your required monthly payment (unless you recast the loan).</li>
      <li><strong>Doesn't change:</strong> escrow amounts (tax/insurance) unless those costs change separately.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="card section prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">Monthly $300 vs a one-time lump sum</h2>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:10px 0 0">
      Earlier payments tend to save more interest because they reduce the balance sooner. That's why a recurring monthly extra can have a
      large impact over time. A one-time lump sum can also help, especially if it happens early in the loan.
    </p>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:12px 0 0">
      Use the <a href="/calculators/extra-payment-calculator">Extra Payment Mortgage Calculator</a> to compare:
    </p>
    <ul class="muted" style="margin:10px 0 0; padding-left:18px">
      <li>$300 extra every month</li>
      <li>$3,600 once per year</li>
      <li>A one-time lump sum (for example, from a bonus)</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="card section prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">If your income is variable</h2>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:10px 0 0">
      If your income changes month to month, consider a smaller fixed extra (like $100) plus occasional lump sums when cash is strong. This
      avoids overcommitting to a payment you cannot sustain while still capturing the benefit of earlier principal reduction.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card section prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">How $300 compares to one extra payment per year</h2>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:10px 0 0">
      One extra payment per year is roughly your monthly P&amp;I divided by 12. On a typical mortgage, that might be around $150 to $250 per
      month. Paying $300 monthly is often a bit more aggressive than the "one extra payment per year" rule of thumb.
    </p>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:12px 0 0">
      If you want a more moderate plan, try $150 or $200 and compare the payoff timeline in the calculator.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card section prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">Payoff vs investing (quick view)</h2>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:10px 0 0">
      Paying extra principal is a guaranteed return equal to your mortgage rate. Investing may offer higher expected returns but with risk
      and volatility. If you are unsure, consider splitting the $300 across extra principal and savings or retirement contributions.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card section prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">Worked example (computed)</h2>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:10px 0 0">
      Example: {money0.format(examplePrincipal)} at {pct2.format(exampleApr)}% APR for {exampleTermMonths} months. Compare baseline to adding
      {money0.format(exampleExtraMonthly)}/month in extra principal.
    </p>
    <div style="overflow:auto; margin-top:12px">
      <table class="table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Scenario</th>
            <th class="num">Extra principal</th>
            <th class="num">Payoff time</th>
            <th class="num">Total interest</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td>Baseline</td>
            <td class="num">{money0.format(0)}</td>
            <td class="num">{base.months} months</td>
            <td class="num">{money0.format(base.totalInterest)}</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>With extra</td>
            <td class="num">{money0.format(exampleExtraMonthly)}</td>
            <td class="num">{withExtra.months} months</td>
            <td class="num">{money0.format(withExtra.totalInterest)}</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:12px 0 0">
      In this example, the $300 extra saves about {money0.format(Math.max(0, base.totalInterest - withExtra.totalInterest))} in interest and
      shortens payoff by {Math.max(0, base.months - withExtra.months)} months.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card section prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">What to confirm with your lender (important)</h2>
    <ul class="muted" style="margin:10px 0 0; padding-left:18px">
      <li>The extra payment is applied as <strong>principal-only</strong> (not "paid ahead").</li>
      <li>How to designate principal-only in online payments (some systems require a checkbox or separate field).</li>
      <li>Whether a prepayment penalty exists (many loans have none; some do).</li>
      <li>Whether a recast is available if you want a lower required payment after a large principal payment.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="card section prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">Checklist: keep it principal-only</h2>
    <ul class="muted" style="margin:10px 0 0; padding-left:18px">
      <li><strong>Use the principal-only option:</strong> confirm the payment is not marked "paid ahead."</li>
      <li><strong>Verify the statement:</strong> check the ending balance after payment posts.</li>
      <li><strong>Keep cash reserves:</strong> don't reduce emergency savings too far.</li>
      <li><strong>Recast if needed:</strong> consider recasting if your goal is a lower required payment.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="card section prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">FAQ</h2>
    <h3 style="margin:12px 0 0">Is $300/month a good target?</h3>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:8px 0 0">
      It depends on your budget and rate. The best amount is one you can sustain without missing payments or dipping into emergency funds.
    </p>
    <h3 style="margin:12px 0 0">Does this reduce my escrow?</h3>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:8px 0 0">
      No. Escrow is separate from principal and interest, so extra payments do not change it.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card section prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">References</h2>
    <ul class="muted" style="margin:10px 0 0; padding-left:18px">
      <li>
        CFPB:{" "}
        <a href="https://www.consumerfinance.gov/consumer-tools/mortgages/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">
          Mortgages resources
        </a>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="card section prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">Next steps</h2>
    <div class="btn-row" style="margin-top:10px">
      <a class="btn btn-primary" href="/calculators/extra-payment-calculator">Model a $300 extra payment</a>
      <a class="btn" href="/calculators/mortgage-payment-calculator">Baseline mortgage payment</a>
      <a class="btn" href="/guides/extra-mortgage-payments">Extra payments guide</a>
    </div>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:12px 0 0">
      Educational use only. Not financial advice.
    </p>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:12px 0 0; font-size:13px">
      Last updated: 2026-01-28
    </p>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
